            "content": "Before writing code, read design.md D1 + spec.md's \"Concurrent move and child-creation cannot produce a stale path\" scenario, then had advisor independently verify a concern. Confirmed real, flagging per your \"stop and report on genuine design contradictions\" instruction.\n\n**The gap:** D1 says move() locks the subtree root FOR UPDATE; createChild() locks its immediate parent FOR UPDATE. Those only contend on the SAME row when the child's parent IS the exact unit being moved. If the child is created under a strict descendant of the moved subtree (not the root itself — which spec.md's \"a unit in that subtree\" phrasing covers), the two operations lock different rows and never serialize.\n\nUnder READ COMMITTED, a plain UPDATE's candidate set is fixed by its statement-start snapshot; blocking mid-scan on a lock only triggers a re-check (EvalPlanQual) for rows already in that set, never for brand-new rows committed by someone else afterward. So: createChild locks descendant X, reads its old path, inserts a child, commits — all while move() is still in flight rewriting the subtree via a different row lock. move()'s own deferred UPDATE never sees the new child row (it postdates its snapshot), so its bulk rewrite skips it. The deferred constraint trigger doesn't catch it either: at createChild's own commit, the parent's path (as far as that transaction can see) is still pre-move and consistent; move() never touches the child row so no trigger fires for it there either. Net result: silent, permanent path/parent inconsistency, with neither serialization nor an abort — the spec's own two required outcomes.\n\n**Fix that stays inside a row-lock primitive:** lock the TREE ROOT (first path segment, one shared row per tree) FOR UPDATE, and lock-BEFORE-read (acquire the lock, then read the path you derive from, not the other way — I found `move()` also has a related staleness bug: it currently computes `oldPrefix` from the caller-supplied `unit.path`, which can already be stale by call time regardless of concurrency). With a shared root lock, whichever operation loses the race blocks at lock acquisition, so its next read happens after the winner commits, and sees consistent state either way. Cross-tree moves would need to lock both roots ordered by id to avoid deadlock (not applicable here — this repo's move() only rehomes within reachable parents, cross-org moves aren't exposed yet).\n\n**Ask:** do you want the tree-root-lock fix folded into 1.5/1.6 now, or is the descendant-race window an acceptable, documented v0.3 limitation (rare, admin-initiated ops) with the literal D1 root+parent locking shipped as specified? I'm proceeding with 1.1–1.4 and all of 2.x now (independent of this), and fixing the unrelated `move()` stale-`oldPrefix` bug (re-reading the path under the lock it already needs to take) regardless of your answer, since that one is unambiguously a bug against the *existing* literal design. I'm holding the \"concurrent move+createChild serializes\" test (1.6) and the final locking shape until you decide.\n\nAlso flagging a secondary point from advisor on 1.1: granting `app_rls` membership to `app` (so `app` can `ALTER FUNCTION ... OWNER TO app_rls` in the migration) also lets `app` `SET ROLE app_rls` and fully bypass RLS at will — the membership itself doesn't grant BYPASSRLS to `app` directly, but `SET ROLE` does let it assume the privilege. PG17 supports `GRANT app_rls TO app WITH SET FALSE`, which keeps the ownership-transfer capability but blocks `SET ROLE`. I'll use that form and verify `ALTER FUNCTION ... OWNER TO` still succeeds under it in the throwaway DB before relying on it — will report back if it doesn't work and I have to fall back to plain `GRANT ... TO app`.",
