llback is weaker\ndefense-in-depth (no independent datastore-level check) and must be called out\nexplicitly wherever it's used, not silently substituted.\n\n`GRANT app_rls TO app` (needed so `app`, which owns every table, can\n`ALTER FUNCTION ... OWNER TO app_rls` in the migration) also lets `app` `SET ROLE\napp_rls` and assume `BYPASSRLS` directly — restricting that with `GRANT ... WITH SET\nFALSE` was tried and rejected: Postgres's `ALTER ... OWNER TO` reuses the same\n`SET ROLE` permission check, so it fails under `WITH SET FALSE` too. This is not a\nnew hole: `app` already owns every table, so it can already run `ALTER TABLE ... NO\nFORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` and disable RLS by DDL alone — a role that can grant\nitself `BYPASSRLS` via membership has no more effective power than a role that can\nalready turn RLS off on tables it owns.\n\n## Conventions",
