            "content": "# Proposal: org-units — production-grade nested org units & memberships\n\n## Why\n\nThe identity layer (#44, SPEC §6.1/§7.1–§7.3) shipped on `stack/split-identity` is well-engineered — ID-based materialized paths, FORCE RLS with a datastore backstop against owner-minting, 13 RLS integration tests — but it carries deliberate deferrals whose rationales have expired or interact dangerously:\n\n1. **Path integrity is app-code-only.** The DB trigger was deferred \"because there is no HTTP surface yet\" — the surface now exists. A concurrent `move` + `createChild` silently corrupts the tree (child materializes a stale path; RLS `WITH CHECK` still passes against the stale ancestors).\n2. **Member visibility is own-rows-only**, which blocks the roster, admin revoke, and role updates (Postgres applies the SELECT policy to UPDATE/DELETE targets — proven during #44 v2 review). Today that accident is also the *only* thing stopping an admin from demoting or revoking an owner (`memberships_update` USING passes for admins on the owner's row). Widening visibility without owner-row guards in the same migration opens a privilege-inversion hole.\n3. **Owners are trapped and orphanable.** No last-owner protection (the sole owner can self-leave, permanently orphaning the org) and no ownership transfer (the owner-mint backstop means an owner can never hand off and leave).\n4. **Admin UX doesn't exist.** You can create orgs and grant memberships but can't see members, remove them, change roles, rename/move/delete units, or do any of it from the web app.\n\nThis change closes the gap between \"passes #44 acceptance\" and \"production-grade governance layer\", before #45 (policy engine) and #46 (config resolver) build on top of it.\n\n## What Changes\n\n- **DB integrity for the materialized path**: a constraint trigger enforcing `path = parent.path || '/' || id` (root: `path = id`) on insert/update of `org_units`, plus row locks in `createChild`/`move` to close the concurrent-move race. Corruption becomes impossible, not just unlikely.\n- **Recursion-safe member visibility**: a `SECURITY DEFINER` helper (`is_org_admin`) so `memberships_select` can grant ancestor owners/admins visibility into unit members without the RLS rewriter cycle.\n- **Owner-row guards, landed in the same migration**: the admin arms of `memberships_update`/`memberships_delete` exclude rows with `role = 'owner'` — admins can never demote or revoke an owner once they can see the row.\n- **Last-owner invariant**: a constraint trigger preventing the deletion/demotion of a unit's last `owner` membership. Roots always retain ≥ 1 owner.\n- **Ownership transfer**: an atomic, owner-initiated transfer flow (the single controlled path that may mint a new `owner`, complementing the existing anti-escalation backstop).\n- **Complete the admin HTTP surface** (the items cut from the #44 v2 slice): member roster (`GET`), admin revoke (`DELETE`), role update (`PATCH`), unit rename/move (`PATCH`), leaf delete (`DELETE`), ownership transfer (`POST`), with the established DTO/OpenAPI/error-semantics conventions (RLS denial → 403, invisible resource → 404, duplicate grant → 409).\n- **Web admin UI**: organization management under settings — org tree, create root/child, roster with role management, leave/remove member, rename/move/delete unit, transfer ownership — composed from `@workspace/ui` per DESIGN.md.\n- **Issue hygiene**: #44's body still describes materialized `inherited_from_id` memberships; the implemented (better) design resolves inheritance at read time. Update the issue when this ships.\n\nNon-goals (stay out): #45 policy engine / deny-overrides-allow, #46 config resolver, email invitations with pending state (grant-by-userId stays; invitation UX is a follow-up), external-identities HTTP surface (channel ingress, v0.9), instance-level restrictions on who may create root orgs (#45 territory).\n\n## Capabilities\n\n### New Capabilities\n\n- `org-units`: nested org-unit lifecycle — create root/child, rename, subtree move, leaf delete; materialized-path consistency as a DB-enforced invariant; RLS visibility scoping.\n- `org-memberships`: membership & role management — grant, revoke, role update, roster visibility, effective-role resolution (nearest-wins), last-owner protection, ownership transfer, anti-escalation guarantees.\n- `org-admin-ui`: web UX for organization management — tree navigation, member roster, role controls, destructive-action confirmation patterns, error surfacing.\n\n### Modified Capabilities\n\n<!-- none — openspec/specs is empty; this change introduces the first capabilities -->\n\n## Impact\n\n- `apps/api/src/db/schema/identity.ts` + a new hand-authored migration (triggers + `SECURITY DEFINER` function + policy changes; precedent: `0013` trigger migration, documented in Gotchas).\n- `apps/api/src/identity/*` — repositories (locking), service (new ops), controller (six new endpoints), DTOs, `openapi.json`.\n- `apps/api/src/identity/identity-rls.integration.spec.ts` + `scripts/rls-test.sh` — new negative tests (admin-cannot-touch-owner, last-owner, roster scoping, transfer, path-trigger rejection).\n- `apps/web` — new settings area for organizations; TanStack Query hooks against the new endpoints.\n- Security surface: RLS policy changes on `memberships` and a `SECURITY DEFINER` function — the highest-risk part of the change; every policy change ships with a cross-tenant negative test in the same commit.\n",
