            "content": "# Design: org-units — production-grade nested org units & memberships\n\n## Context\n\n`stack/split-identity` already ships (see proposal for the assessment):\n\n- `org_units` / `memberships` / `external_identities` tables, FORCE RLS, ID-based materialized paths (`rootId/childId/…`), DB-enforced role enum (SPEC §7.3).\n- Pure helpers (`org-path.ts`, `role-resolution.ts`) + unit tests; 13 RLS integration tests.\n- `IdentityService` with single-tx root bootstrap (org never created ownerless); SQLSTATE→HTTP mapping (23505→409, 23503→404, 42501→403).\n- HTTP surface: `POST /org-units`, `POST /:id/children`, `GET /org-units`, `POST /:id/memberships` (grant, role ∈ {admin, member} only — the DTO-level owner-mint guard).\n- Deliberate deferrals recorded in `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-07-03-org-membership-admin-surface-design.md`: roster, revoke, role update, owner transfer, rename/move/delete surface, invitations.\n\nHard constraints this design works inside:\n\n- **RLS recursion**: a policy on `org_units` may scan `memberships`, but `memberships_select` must stay terminal (no `org_units` reference) — otherwise the rewriter cycles. Any widening of member visibility must break the cycle another way.\n- **SELECT policy gates UPDATE/DELETE targets**: proven during #44 v2 — an admin cannot UPDATE/DELETE a row their SELECT policy hides. Today this *accidentally* protects owner rows from admins; visibility widening must not silently remove that protection.\n- **Migrations**: drizzle-kit generated; triggers/functions/`FORCE` are hand-authored (precedents `0004`, `0011`, `0013`, `0018`) and documented in `apps/api/CLAUDE.md` Gotchas.\n- `TenantDbService.runAs` wraps each unit of work in ONE transaction with `app.current_user_id` set transaction-locally — multi-statement repository ops (`move`) are already atomic.\n\n## Goals / Non-Goals\n\n**Goals:**\n\n- Make materialized-path consistency a database invariant (trigger + locking), not a repository convention.\n- Widen member visibility recursion-safely, and land owner-row guards in the same migration so the widening cannot enable owner demotion/revocation by admins.\n- Enforce the last-owner invariant and provide the one controlled owner-minting path (transfer).\n- Complete the admin HTTP surface and a web UI for it, matching existing API/UX conventions.\n\n**Non-Goals:**\n\n- Policy engine, deny-overrides-allow, approvals (#45). Config resolution (#46).\n- Email invitations / pending memberships; user search/autocomplete (grant stays by userId).\n- External-identities HTTP surface (channel ingress, v0.9).\n- Instance-level policy on root-org creation (any authenticated user may create a root, as today).\n- Materializing inherited memberships (read-time resolution stays; #44's issue body will be corrected).\n\n## Decisions\n\n### D1. Path integrity: constraint trigger + row locks (both, not either)\n\n**Trigger** (hand-authored migration, like `0013`): `BEFORE INSERT OR UPDATE OF path, parent_id ON org_units` — validates `parent_id IS NULL → path = id::text` and `parent_id IS NOT NULL → path = (SELECT path FROM org_units WHERE id = parent_id) || '/' || id::text`. Rejects any write that would desynchronize the tree, from any code path (repository bug, future internal script, manual SQL).\n\n**Locks** (repository): `createChild` reads the parent `FOR SHARE`; `move` locks the moved unit's row and the new parent `FOR SHARE`/`FOR UPDATE` **in deterministic id order** before rewriting. Without locks, the trigger would turn the `move`+`createChild` race into a runtime error for the innocent transaction; with locks, the race serializes and both commit consistently. The trigger is the backstop; the locks are the UX.\n\n*Alternative considered*: `pg_advisory_xact_lock` on the root id — coarser (serializes all writes per tree), simpler deadlock story. Rejected for now: row locks are enough at this scale and don't serialize unrelated subtrees. Revisit if deadlocks show up in practice.\n\n*Note*: the trigger reads the parent row as the trigger's invoker — under FORCE RLS the parent must be visible, which it always is for legitimate writers (insert/update RLS already requires admin-on-path). The trigger function is `SECURITY DEFINER` with pinned `search_path` to avoid RLS interplay entirely and keep the invariant unconditional.\n\n### D2. Member visibility: `SECURITY DEFINER is_org_admin()` + a second SELECT-policy arm\n\nNew function (hand-authored migration):\n\n```sql\nCREATE FUNCTION is_org_admin(p_user text, p_org_unit uuid) RETURNS boolean\nLANGUAGE sql STABLE SECURITY DEFINER SET search_path = public AS $$\n  SELECT EXISTS (\n    SELECT 1 FROM org_units u\n    JOIN memberships m\n      ON m.org_unit_id::text = ANY(string_to_array(u.path, '/'))\n    WHERE u.id = p_org_unit\n      AND m.user_id = p_user\n      AND m.role IN ('owner','admin')\n  );\n$$;\n```\n\n`SECURITY DEFINER` runs as the table owner, bypassing RLS inside the function — this is what breaks the recursion cycle without restructuring the policy graph. `memberships_select` becomes:\n\n```\nuser_id = current_user  OR  is_org_admin(current_user, memberships.org_unit_id)\n```\n\nGuardrails: `STABLE`, pinned `search_path`, takes the user from `current_setting('app.current_user_id', true)` — **decision: pass it explicitly as an argument is rejected**; the function reads the setting itself so it cannot be called with an arbitrary user id from a policy context (`is_org_admin(p_org_unit uuid)`, single argument). `REVOKE EXECUTE FROM PUBLIC` is unnecessary (it only reveals booleans about org-admin-ness the caller's own policies already imply) but cheap — do it anyway.\n\n*Alternative considered*: restructure policies so `memberships` self-join carries visibility (no function). Rejected: every attempt reintroduces the memberships→org_units→memberships cycle; the definer function is the standard, auditable escape hatch.\n\n*Scope*: visibility for owners/admins only, not plain members. SPEC §7.3 gives roster reads to admin-tier; member-tier roster can be added later by widening the same arm — one line, not a redesign.\n\n### D3. Owner-row guards land in the same migration as D2 (privilege-inversion coupling)\n\nToday `memberships_update`/`memberships_delete` admin arms would permit demoting/revoking an `owner` row — masked only by the own-rows SELECT policy hiding the target. D2 removes the mask, so the same migration tightens:\n\n- `memberships_update` USING (admin arm): `... AND role <> 'owner'` — admins cannot select owner rows *for update* at all (USING, not just WITH CHECK, so the existing-row role is checked).\n- `memberships_delete` (admin arm): `... AND role <> 'owner'`. Self-leave arm (`user_id = current_user`) stays — but is now subordinated to the last-owner trigger (D4).\n\nResult: owner rows are immutable/irrevocable through the general paths; the *only* owner mutations are bootstrap (existing insert branch) and transfer (D5). These two policy edits and D2 are one atomic migration — reviewers should treat a split as a defect.\n\n### D4. Last-owner invariant: constraint trigger on `memberships`\n\n`AFTER UPDATE OR DELETE ON memberships` (constraint trigger, deferrable initially immediate): if the old row had `role = 'owner'` and the unit now has zero `owner` memberships → raise. Root units therefore always keep ≥ 1 owner (bootstrap guarantees the first; the trigger guarantees survival). Child units typically have no owner rows — the trigger only fires when a unit that *had* an owner would lose its last one, so children are unaffected.\n\nService layer maps the trigger's error (custom SQLSTATE via `ERRCODE`, e.g. `raise ... using errcode = 'LLOW1'`... **decision: use a message-tagged `check_violation` instead** — custom SQLSTATEs are opaque; `23514` + a stable trigger name in the message maps cleanly to 409 with a \"transfer ownership first\" hint).\n\n### D5. Ownership transfer: `SECURITY DEFINER transfer_org_ownership(p_org_unit uuid, p_new_owner text)`\n\nThe single controlled path that mints `owner` outside bootstrap. Atomic, in one function:\n\n1. Assert caller (`current_setting('app.current_user_id')`) holds an **explicit** `owner` membership on `p_org_unit` (not inherited — transferring a child you own via ancestry is meaningless; the owner row lives where it lives).\n2. Assert `p_new_owner` has an explicit membership on the unit (any role) — transfer is a promotion of a known member, not a grant to a stranger.\n3. `UPDATE` target row → `owner`; `UPDATE` caller row → `admin`.\n\nExposed as `POST /org-units/:id/ownership-transfers { newOwnerUserId }` (a resource-ish action; a pure `PATCH` on two membership rows can't be atomic from the client). The function is the *only* thing with rights to write `role = 'owner'` post-bootstrap; RLS policies (D3) don't need a carve-out because `SECURITY DEFINER` bypasses them — which is exactly why the function body must re-check authorization itself (step 1) and be reviewed as security-critical code.\n\n*Alternative considered*: two-step (grant owner + self-demote) via relaxed policies. Rejected: a window with two owners is fine, but a crash between steps leaves permanent dual-ownership, and relaxing the anti-mint backstop for a general path reopens what #44 deliberately closed.\n\n### D6. HTTP surface & error semantics\n\n| Endpoint | Semantics |\n| --- | --- |\n| `GET /org-units/:id/memberships` | Roster; visible to unit/ancestor owner+admin (D2). 404 if unit invisible. |\n| `PATCH /org-units/:id/memberships/:userId { role }` | Role update, role ∈ {admin, maintainer, member, viewer, guest} (DTO excludes `owner` + `service_account`); owner rows unreachable (D3) → 404/403; last-owner unaffected (target isn't owner by construction). |\n| `DELETE /org-units/:id/memberships/:userId` | Admin revoke (owner rows unreachable) or self-leave; last-owner trigger → 409 + hint. 204. |\n| `PATCH /org-units/:id { name?, parentId? }` | Rename and/or move (move = owner/admin on both source and destination path — RLS USING checks old path, WITH CHECK new path, already in place). Move into own subtree → 422. |\n| `DELETE /org-units/:id` | Leaf-only (FK `RESTRICT` → 409 with \"delete children first\"), owner-only (existing RLS). 204. |\n| `POST /org-units/:id/ownership-transfers` | D5. 201/204; 403 non-owner; 404 target not a member. |\n\nConvention continuity: invisible resource → **404** (anti-enumeration), RLS write denial → **403**, conflicts → **409**, all via the existing `pgErrorCode` mapping extended with the trigger-tagged 23514s. Grant keeps `userId` input; the FK-violation→404 user-existence oracle is accepted for v0.3 (self-hosted instance, authenticated users only) and noted in the spec.\n\n### D7. Web UI: settings-scoped organization management\n\nNew route group `apps/web/app/(chat)/settings/organizations` (the settings area already exists):\n\n- **Org list + tree**: visible units rendered as a tree (client-side from `path` — parents sort before children by path order, depth = path length); create root; create child on a node.\n- **Unit page**: rename inline; move via parent-picker (excluding own subtree — mirror the server rule client-side for immediate feedback, server remains authoritative); roster table (role badge, role select for admin+, remove button); leave-org action; danger zone (delete leaf unit, transfer ownership) with `AlertDialog` confirmation naming the consequence.\n- Role controls render only what the caller may do (from their effective role via `resolveRole`-backed endpoint data) but never *rely* on that — the API is the gate.\n- TanStack Query for all data; mutations invalidate the org/roster queries; `@workspace/ui` primitives and DESIGN.md tokens throughout; no ad-hoc colors.\n\n*UX decisions*: destructive actions always name the object (\"Remove Alice from Platform?\"); 409 last-owner surfaces as an inline explanation with a \"Transfer ownership\" call-to-action, not a toast; empty states guide the first org creation (\"Create your organization / household\").\n\n### D8. `service_account` handling (defer, but stop the bleeding)\n\n`service_account` as a *role rank* is a modeling smell (it's an identity kind), but re-modeling it is #45-adjacent. Decision: exclude `service_account` from every new DTO enum (grant already excludes it; role-update DTO must too) so no surface can assign it, and leave the enum value in place. Re-modeling happens with the policy engine.\n\n## Risks / Trade-offs\n\n- [SECURITY DEFINER function has RLS-bypass power] → Function bodies are minimal, `STABLE` where read-only, pinned `search_path`, read the acting user only from `app.current_user_id`, and each ships with cross-tenant negative tests in `identity-rls.integration.spec.ts` + `rls-test.sh` in the same commit. Treat any edit to these functions as security-review-required.\n- [Policy widening (D2) and owner guards (D3) could be split by a careless rebase] → Single migration file; the RLS spec gains a test that *fails if D2 exists without D3* (admin attempts owner demotion — must be 0 rows affected).\n- [Trigger errors surface as 500s if unmapped] → Extend `pgErrorCode` mapping + integration tests asserting 409/422 bodies, not raw 500s.\n- [Row-lock ordering deadlocks under concurrent moves] → Deterministic lock order (by uuid); moves are rare, admin-initiated ops; acceptable residual risk, monitored via pg logs. Fallback documented: advisory lock per root.\n- [Tree rendering from `path` in the UI degrades on huge orgs] → Fine for v0.3 scale (self-hosted, hundreds of units); pagination/virtualization is a follow-up, noted in code.\n- [No invitation consent — admins add users directly] → Accepted for v0.3 (same-instance, authenticated); spec records it as a conscious decision so the invitations follow-up has a clear anchor.\n\n## Migration Plan\n\nOne hand-authored migration (documented in `apps/api/CLAUDE.md` Gotchas, like `0013`/`0018`):\n\n1. `is_org_admin` function + `memberships_select` second arm (D2) **and** owner-row guards on update/delete policies (D3) — atomic.\n2. Path-integrity trigger (D1) — existing rows are consistent (repository-maintained + tests); trigger validates go-forward writes only, no backfill needed. A one-off `DO` block asserts full-table consistency at migration time and aborts if violated (fail loud, not silent).\n3. Last-owner constraint trigger (D4) + `transfer_org_ownership` (D5).\n\nRollback: standard down-migration dropping triggers/function and restoring prior policies; no data changes to revert. Deploy is api-only until the web UI PR; endpoints are additive.\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Should `maintainer`+ (not just admin+) see the roster? SPEC §7.3 is silent; defaulting to admin-tier, widen later if project UX needs it.\n- Transfer target must already be a member (D5.2) — or should transfer auto-grant membership? Current answer: must be a member (explicitness beats convenience for an owner-level action).\n- Does `GET /org-units` need subtree filtering (`?under=<id>`) for the UI, or is client-side tree assembly from the flat visible list enough at v0.3 scale? Default: flat list, assemble client-side.\n",
