            "content": "## Summary\n\nConsent-based member addition: **invitations with a pending state**, replacing (or wrapping) the direct admin grant-by-userId flow for humans.\n\n## Context\n\nThe org-units change (#44 hardening) deliberately keeps `POST /org-units/:id/memberships { userId }` — an admin adds any known user directly, without the target's consent. Two accepted-for-v0.3 consequences, recorded in the change's design doc:\n\n- No consent step — you can be added to an org without ever agreeing.\n- The FK-violation→404 mapping is a mild **user-existence oracle** (probe userIds via grant attempts). Low risk same-instance, but real.\n\nFine for a household; wrong for org-shaped or public-ish instances.\n\n## Design sketch\n\n- `membership_invitations` entity: unit, role (non-owner), invited-by, invitee (userId or email), token, expiry, status (`pending | accepted | declined | revoked | expired`).\n- Add-by-email with **generic responses** (no existence oracle: inviting an unknown email looks identical to a known one).\n- Accept/decline surface for the invitee (in-app; email delivery optional/later).\n- Admin can revoke pending invitations; roster UI shows pending state.\n- Grant-by-userId either becomes invitation-only or stays for `service_account`/automation contexts — decide in design.\n\n## Sequencing\n\nAfter the org-units hardening change (roster/revoke/role-update are prerequisites for managing invitations sensibly). Independent of #45.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Invitation lifecycle (create/accept/decline/revoke/expire) with RLS scoping + cross-tenant negative tests.\n- [ ] No user-existence oracle through any invitation surface.\n- [ ] Roster UI shows and manages pending invitations.\n- [ ] Accepting creates the membership through the standard guarded path (role enum still excludes `owner`).\n",
