            "content": "## Summary\n\n`service_account` is modeled as an **org role** (SPEC §7.3 / `org_role` enum), but it is an **identity kind**, not a role rank — re-model it alongside the policy engine.\n\n## Context\n\n- Nearest-wins role resolution (#44) has no meaningful semantics for `service_account` (what does \"service_account overrides inherited admin\" mean?).\n- Every membership-mutating DTO must remember to exclude it from role enums (grant and role-update already do) — a recurring footgun rather than a modeled concept.\n- SPEC §7.3 itself describes it as \"used by connectors and automations, never interactive by default\" — that's a property of the *principal*, not of its position in a scope.\n\n## Design sketch (to be settled with #45)\n\n- Represent service accounts as a user/principal kind (`users.kind = 'service_account'` or a dedicated principals table), holding ordinary roles (`member`, `maintainer`, …) within scopes.\n- Policy engine (#45) gates what service-account principals may do (never interactive, capability allowlists).\n- Migration: remove `service_account` from `org_role` once nothing references it (additive enum values are easy; removal needs a sweep).\n\n## Sequencing\n\nWith or immediately after #45 — the policy engine is what gives service accounts real semantics. Until then the value stays in the enum, excluded from every DTO.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Service accounts are principals with ordinary scoped roles; `org_role` no longer contains `service_account`.\n- [ ] DTO-level exclusions become unnecessary and are removed.\n- [ ] SPEC §7.3 updated to reflect the split (role vocabulary vs principal kinds).\n",
