            "new_string": "### D2. Member visibility: `is_org_admin()` owned by a dedicated `BYPASSRLS` role + a second SELECT-policy arm\n\n**The naive fix does not work here, and knowing why is load-bearing**: a plain `SECURITY DEFINER` function runs as its owner — which is `app`, the table owner — and `0018` sets `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY`, which subjects the owner to the policies too. Inside such a function the `memberships` scan would re-trigger `memberships_select`, which calls the function again → runtime recursion (stack-depth error), not a bypass. Only superusers and roles with the `BYPASSRLS` attribute bypass RLS.\n\nMechanism, therefore:\n\n- `docker/postgres/initdb/01-app-role.sql` (and the rls-test / e2e throwaway-DB harnesses) additionally provision `app_privileged` — `NOLOGIN NOSUPERUSER BYPASSRLS`, granted to `app` so migrations can `ALTER FUNCTION ... OWNER TO app_privileged`.\n- The migration creates the function and reassigns ownership; a `DO` block asserts the role exists first and aborts loudly with an upgrade hint (existing deployments must re-provision before migrating).\n\n```sql\nCREATE FUNCTION is_org_admin(p_org_unit uuid) RETURNS boolean\nLANGUAGE sql STABLE SECURITY DEFINER SET search_path = public AS $$\n  SELECT EXISTS (\n    SELECT 1 FROM org_units u\n    JOIN memberships m\n      ON m.org_unit_id::text = ANY(string_to_array(u.path, '/'))\n    WHERE u.id = p_org_unit\n      AND m.user_id = current_setting('app.current_user_id', true)\n      AND m.role IN ('owner','admin')\n  );\n$$;\nALTER FUNCTION is_org_admin(uuid) OWNER TO app_privileged;\n```\n\n`memberships_select` becomes:\n\n```\nuser_id = current_user  OR  is_org_admin(memberships.org_unit_id)\n```\n\nGuardrails: **single argument** — the function reads the acting user from `current_setting` itself, so no policy or caller can evaluate admin-ness for an arbitrary user; `STABLE`; pinned `search_path`; `REVOKE EXECUTE FROM PUBLIC` (cheap, do it).\n\nAccepted trade-off (state it, 